ni when faced with unpopular, hateful, or dangerous speech. Timely and vitally important, Speak Freely shows why universities can succeed only by fostering more free speech, more free thought-and a greater tolerance for both.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aAcademic freedomzUnited States. 0aEducation, HigherzUnited StatesxPhilosophy. 0aFreedom of speechzUnited States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Censorship.2bisacsh  a1st Amendment.  aAlexander Meiklejohn.  aAllan Bloom.  aAmerican Civil Liberties Union.  aBari Weiss.  aBill Maher.  aFirst Amendment.  aJohn Stuart Mill.  aMcCarthyism.  aThe Closing of the American Mind.  aThe Coddling of the American Mind.  aacademic freedom.  acampus Republicans.  acampus diversity.  acancel culture.  acensorship on campus.  acensorship.  aconservatism.  afree expression.  afree speech on campus.  afreedom of speech.  aliberal indoctrination.  aliberalism.  aonline shaming.  apolitical correctness.  aspeech as violence.  astudent groups.  awoke McCarthyism.1 aWhittington, Keith E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691193595zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691193595423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780691193595/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles